"1325":"1325","1401":"1401","1398":"1398","1298":"1298","1364":"1364","Bef 1359":"before 1359","1285":"1285","Abt 1316":"about 1316","Chipping Campden, Gloucestershire, England":"Chipping Campden, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","North Bradley, Wiltshire, England":"England","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Southwick, Wiltshire, England":"Southwick, Wiltshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Neuville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French, Walloon, and Flemish: habitational name from (La) Neuville, the name of several places mainly in the northern part of France and in Belgium (Wallonia and Flanders), ultimately derived from Latin <i>nova villa</i> ‘new country house, estate’ (later, ‘new settlement/village/town’). Compare   Newville  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Newville","meanings":["Americanized form of French, Walloon, and Flemish   Neuville  .","Possibly also Irish and English: variant of   Neville  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Neuville was born in 1298, in Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom. She married John Grivelle in 1315, in Chipping Campden, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She died in 1364, at the age of 66."},"et":{"1298–1364":"1298–1364","1285–1359":"1285–1359","1316–1401":"1316–1401","1325–1398":"1325–1398","1325–Male":"1325–Surnud","1316":"1316","1315":"1315","1359":"1359","1325":"1325","1401":"1401","1398":"1398","1298":"1298","1364":"1364","Bef 1359":"enne 1359","1285":"1285","Abt 1316":"umbes 1316","Chipping Campden, Gloucestershire, England":"Chipping Campden